AB  - Ports worldwide face critical energy and environmental challenges due to diesel generator dependency, with growing electricity demand from operations exceeding capacity, requiring sustainable shore power solutions for netzero targets. Microgrid implementation, integrating renewable energy sources such as photovoltaic arrays and energy storage, represents a promising solution for reducing fossil fuel dependency while enhancing operational resilience and efficiency. This research focuses on power flow simulation and emission analysis of a hybrid photovoltaic and grid electricity system featuring a rooftop PV installation at Tanjung Emas Port, with a capacity of 6,250 kWp. The simulation examines normal operational conditions and photovoltaic intermittency scenarios to assess system performance. It confirms that voltage levels remain within the IEC 60038 range of 0.90 to 1.10 per unit under both conditions. The islanded PV system successfully supplies outlet boxes at both terminals and office buildings despite minimum irradiance. This solar-powered shore power system achieves emission reduction of 61.39% compared to diesel-based systems, providing a technical foundation for advancing Tanjung Emas Port toward becoming an international smart port.  © 2025 IEEE.
