DO  - 10.1109/ISRITI68345.2025.11393219
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105035734828?origin=resultslist
AB  - Sustainable port operations and efficient container handling are essential components of competitiveness in modern maritime logistics. Although machine learning (ML) has been widely applied to port operations, particularly for berth scheduling, crane allocation, and yard optimization, current approaches generally emphasize operational efficiency and rarely integrate sustainability requirements. This gap limits the capacity of predictive systems to support emerging Smart Port environments, where performance must align with Environmental, Social, and Governance (ESG) principles. To address this need, this study develops an ESG-driven predictive framework for estimating container turnaround time using six ML algorithms: Generalized Linear Model (GLM), Deep Learning, Decision Tree, Random Forest, Gradient Boosted Trees, and Support Vector Machine. Historical operational characteristics, such as berth time, crane efficiency, loading and unloading rates, and delay factors, were analyzed utilizing RapidMiner. Experimental results indicate that GLM attains the lowest Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) of 0.175, while providing the fastest runtime of 7 seconds, surpassing more complex ensemble methods and neural network models. These findings demonstrate that operational variables display strong linear correlations with turnaround efficiency, thereby rendering GLM appropriate for real-time decision support. By integrating ESG considerations into the predictive process, the proposed model improves environmental performance, reinforces governance coordination, and promotes social workload equilibrium. This study presents a computationally effective methodology for the sustainability-oriented transformation of smart ports. © 2025 IEEE.
