AB  - Smart ports require more effective storage space allocation strategies, and advanced automation in modern terminals enhances both accuracy and efficiency. This study focuses on a new automated container terminal equipped with unilateral cantilever rail-mounted gantry cranes (URMGCs). To compare the new automated, non-Automated, and traditional automated terminals, three mathematical models were developed. Numerical results demonstrate that the new automated container terminal effectively reduces both operation time and cost, with the impacts varying depending on the terminal type. For non-Automated terminals, the reduction in operation time decreases from 20.4% to 13.7% as the number of inbound containers increases, while cost savings stabilize at around 24%. In contrast, traditional automated terminals show a decline in operational efficiency improvements, from 79.4% to 61.1%, but experience more significant cost reductions, growing from 48.5% to 69% as the number of containers increases. These findings provide terminal operators with data-driven insights for optimizing investments and upgrading strategies to enhance both operational efficiency and cost-effectiveness.  © 2025 The Authors.
