AB  - Brazil is a major player in international trade, with Port of Santos featuring amongst the 50 biggest container ports in the world. Thus, especially since the World Trade Organization’s most recent trade facilitation agreement amendment, it is vital for Brazilian ports to become smart. This is a daunting task for Brazil, a developing country well known for its bureaucratic and regulatory challenges. This article looks at the challenges that Brazil, as a developing country, would have to face up to when implementing the smart port policy. The amendment in 2014 to the Marrakesh Agreement establishing the WTO meant that Brazil, as a signatory state to the amended Annex 1a, must take active steps to better facilitate trade through the use of technology and data systems. This article reasons too that the smart port and customs dimension could not be examined without contextualising it against the recent legal and regulatory changes made to port ownership models and port services liberalisation. © 2022, Sweet and Maxwell. All rights reserved.
